I don=E2=80=99t think that anything interesting turns on whether or not thi=
s weekend=E2=80=99s resolution of=C2=A0Silicon Valley Bank was a =E2=80=9Cb=
ailout,=E2=80=9D so let=E2=80=99s not discuss that.
  [1]
=C2=A0But when people talk about bank bailouts, what they often mean to tal=
k about is moral hazard, the idea that if the government saves=C2=A0people =
from the consequences of bad bank behavior, that will encourage more bad ba=
nk behavior in the future. And that seems worth talking about.
It is, I think, fair to say that Silicon Valley Bank took some bad risks, a=
nd that=E2=80=99s why it ended up failing. It is a bit harder to say exactl=
y what SVB=E2=80=99s bad decision was. A simple answer is =E2=80=9Cit made =
a huge bet on interest rates staying low, which most prudent banks would no=
t have done, and it blew up.=E2=80=9D Yesterday   Bloomberg reported that =
=E2=80=9Cin late 2020, the firm=E2=80=99s asset-liability committee receive=
d an internal recommendation to buy shorter-term bonds as more deposits flo=
wed in,=E2=80=9D to reduce its duration risk, but that would have reduced e=
arnings, and so =E2=80=9Cexecutives balked=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccontinued =
to plow cash into higher-yielding assets.=E2=80=9D They took imprudent dura=
tion risk, ignored objections,=C2=A0and it blew them up.
I think that answer is fine. A   more complicated answer would be that they=
 took duration risk, as banks generally do, but their real sin was having a=
 concentrated set of=C2=A0depositors=C2=A0who were uninsured, quick-moving,=
 well-informed, herd-like and very rates-sensitive in their own businesses:=
 If all of your money is demand deposits from tech startups who will withdr=
aw it at the slightest sign of trouble and/or higher rates, you should not =
be investing it in long-term bonds. This is a more subtle answer than =E2=
=80=9Cjust hedge your rate risk bro,=E2=80=9D and it is arguably more=C2=A0=
understandable=C2=A0that SVB=E2=80=99s executives would get it wrong,
  [2]
=C2=A0but in any case it certainly ended up being a bad risk.
So if SVB was=C2=A0rewarded=C2=A0for taking these risks that blew it up, th=
at would be bad; that would be =E2=80=9Cmoral hazard.=E2=80=9D But the way =
the Silicon Valley Bank resolution worked is:
=09SVB was seized by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. on Friday, and by =
Sunday night the FDIC and other regulators announced that all of SVB=E2=80=
=99s depositors =E2=80=94=C2=A0including those who were above the FDIC=E2=
=80=99s usual $250,000 insurance limit =E2=80=94=C2=A0would be able to get =
all of their money back on Monday. So the depositors were fully rescued.=09=
The shareholders, bondholders and executives were not: The executives were =
removed; the shares, which closed at $267.83 last Wednesday, are almost cer=
tainly worth zero
  [3]
; the bonds are also   probably impaired=C2=A0and possibly a zero.

What lessons will rational actors take from this? I mean:
=09If you are a depositor =E2=80=94=C2=A0in particular, a business that nee=
ds more than $250,000 of cash to operate efficiently =E2=80=94=C2=A0you sho=
uld be much less concerned about risk-taking by your bank, because if your =
bank fails the government will probably rescue you.=09If you are a bank exe=
cutive or shareholder or probably bondholder, you should be=C2=A0more=C2=A0=
concerned about risk-taking by your bank, because you have seen that it can=
 lead to executives and shareholders and bondholders getting zeroed, and th=
at the government won=E2=80=99t rescue you if that happens.

And so the question is: Is that moral hazard? Well, not for shareholders an=
d executives and bondholders. I suppose it is moral hazard for depositors, =
and a resolution of SVB that left depositors with losses would force deposi=
tors to pay closer attention to the risks their banks are taking. (Cliff As=
ness  on Twitter: =E2=80=9CThe moral hazard here is we=E2=80=99ve greatly r=
educed the incentive for depositors of any size now =E2=80=A6 to actually g=
ive a moment=E2=80=99s thought to the riskiness of where they=E2=80=99re pu=
tting their money.=E2=80=9D)
But I think the modern bank-regulatory view is=C2=A0that=C2=A0the point of =
a bank deposit is that you shouldn=E2=80=99t have to worry about it, and th=
at it is a=C2=A0failure=C2=A0of bank regulation if depositors of any size h=
ave =E2=80=9Cto actually give a moment=E2=80=99s thought to the riskiness=
=E2=80=9D of a bank. (Bank deposits are meant to be =E2=80=9Cinformation in=
sensitive.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0There are vast areas of life where we don=E2=80=
=99t worry about moral hazard. We don=E2=80=99t say things like =E2=80=9Cth=
e moral hazard of food safety regulation is that we=E2=80=99ve greatly redu=
ced the incentive for consumers to give a moment=E2=80=99s thought to the r=
iskiness of their supermarket=E2=80=99s supply chain.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=
=99s not a thing you=E2=80=99re supposed to think about!=C2=A0
Similarly the riskiness of a bank=E2=80=99s asset/liability mix is absolute=
ly a thing that lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0bank executives, bank directo=
rs, bank regulators, bank shareholders, bank derivatives counterparties =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0are supposed to think about.
  [4]
=C2=A0But not, generally, in 2023, depositors. Opening a bank account, for =
an individual human but also for a business that needs more than $250,000 i=
n cash to conduct business efficiently, is not meant to be a high-stakes in=
vestment decision that requires extensive due diligence.
  [5]
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a bank account! It=E2=80=99s just supposed to work.
  [6]

This is not a universal view. In the olden days, bank depositors=C2=A0did=
=C2=A0think more about their bank=E2=80=99s creditworthiness, and I suppose=
 there is a market-discipline=C2=A0argument that, like, if depositors monit=
or creditworthiness then only the good banks will attract deposits and so t=
he bad banks won=E2=80=99t be able to grow and take risks. But in practice =
I do not think anyone would much like a market where depositors evaluate ba=
nks on their creditworthiness. For one thing, doesn=E2=80=99t it sound exha=
usting? Don=E2=80=99t you have better things to do? For another thing, SVB=
=E2=80=99s depositors kind of=C2=A0did=C2=A0that: They woke up one day, not=
iced that SVB=E2=80=99s balance sheet was bad, and withdrew all their money=
 at once, leading to a banking crisis. Why do we want more of that? For a t=
hird thing, the likely outcome of a rule like=C2=A0=E2=80=9Conly deposit mo=
ney in banks you are sure won=E2=80=99t fail=E2=80=9D would probably be to =
drive more deposits to giant too-big-to-fail banks, which is maybe a fine o=
utcome economically but not likely to be popular.
Still, there really is a moral hazard in banking and in information-insensi=
tive deposits. Schematically, a bank consists of shareholders taking $10 of=
 their own money and $90 of depositors=E2=80=99 money and making some bets =
(home loans, business loans, bond investments, whatever) with that combined=
 pile of money. If the bets pay off, the shareholders get the upside (the d=
epositors just get their deposits back). If the bets lose, the shareholders=
 lose money (the depositors get their money back before shareholders get an=
ything). If the bets lose really big =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the bank bets $100 a=
nd ends up with $50 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the shareholders lose all their mon=
ey, but=C2=A0the depositors get their money back: If the bank is left with =
only $50, the government gives the depositors the other $40.
If you are a rational bank shareholder (or, more to the point, a bank=C2=A0=
executive=C2=A0who owns shares and gets paid for increasing shareholder val=
ue), this structure encourages you to take risk. If you bet $100 on a coin =
flip and you win, the bank has $200, and the shareholders keep $110 of that=
, a 1,000% return. If you lose, the bank has $0, and the shareholders lose =
$10 of that, a -100% return. The expected value of this bet, for the shareh=
olders, is positive. The expected value for the depositors is neutral: Eith=
er way they get their $90 back, either from the bank or from the government=
. The expected value for the government is negative: If the bank wins, the =
government gets nothing; if the bank loses, the government=C2=A0pays the de=
positors $90. But the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0really the executives =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0are the ones who get to decide what bets to take.
(The finance-y way to say this is that the shareholders have a call=C2=A0op=
tion on the bank=E2=80=99s assets, struck at the face value of its deposits=
. An option=E2=80=99s value increases with volatility, so the shareholders =
should want the assets to be volatile. This is roughly true of every compan=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholders always have an option on the company=E2=
=80=99s assets struck at the face value of its debts =E2=80=94=C2=A0but (1)=
 most companies are way less leveraged than banks, so the option is less at=
-the-money and (2) at most companies the option is=C2=A0*priced*, because t=
he debt comes from bondholders who are information-sensitive and won=E2=80=
=99t give the shareholders cheap debt if they=E2=80=99re taking wild risks.=
 At banks, because of the (reasonable) social desire to make deposits infor=
mation-insensitive, the deposits are cheap and the option is not priced.)
This is all true of all banking, to the extent that deposit insurance and l=
ender-of-last-resort mechanisms exist, but certainly it is=C2=A0more=C2=A0t=
rue when the government expands its protection of depositors. But it=C2=A0i=
s=C2=A0true of all banking, which is why there is so much bank regulation. =
Because the=C2=A0 standard solution to this problem is regulation and gover=
nment supervision: The government says to banks =E2=80=9Clook, we all under=
stand that you are effectively making bets with government money, so we are=
 going to keep a close eye on the bets you are making to prevent you from l=
osing our money.=E2=80=9D
The modern view that bank deposits should be safe and information-insensiti=
ve kind of goes along with a modern view that=C2=A0banks are public-private=
 partnerships, that a bank is sort of a business partner with the governmen=
t in taking deposits and providing credit, and that the way the partnership=
 works is that the bank=E2=80=99s executives make the day-to-day decisions =
but the government has a lot of input into and oversight over those decisio=
ns.
On that view, you should probably draw two related=C2=A0conclusions from SV=
B:
=09Regulators and supervisors probably should have stopped SVB from taking =
dumb risks, they missed something, and changes should be made so they don=
=E2=80=99t miss those same things again.=09The regulators=E2=80=99=C2=A0res=
ponse=C2=A0to SVB=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0guaranteeing all depositors, but also=
 the Fed=E2=80=99s Bank Term Funding Program to finance other banks=E2=80=
=99 bond portfolios at par
  [7]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 increases the value of=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks=E2=80=99 optio=
nality, which encourages=C2=A0them=C2=A0to take more risk, because their de=
posits are safer. (I suppose this is the real moral hazard concern.) And so=
 there should be more regulatory and supervisory changes to tamp down the o=
ther banks=E2=80=99 risks.

The first conclusion seems sort of obvious. If the goal is to make it so de=
positors don=E2=80=99t have to think about the risks banks are taking with =
their money, somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=A0the regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0hav=
e to think about those risks instead. I am not going to sit here and tell y=
ou what SVB=E2=80=99s regulators and supervisors=C2=A0should=C2=A0have done=
 to prevent its meltdown last week, though I=E2=80=99m sure other people wi=
ll. But a few points:
=09=E2=80=9CThe Federal Reserve said Monday it is   launching an internal r=
eview of its supervision and regulation of Silicon Valley Bank after its fa=
ilure last week.=E2=80=9D The report will be released publicly by May 1. So=
 the Fed=C2=A0will eventually tell you what it should have done to prevent =
SVB=E2=80=99s meltdown.=09Bank regulators spend a lot of time thinking abou=
t=C2=A0liquidity=C2=A0requirements for banks. The idea of liquidity rules i=
s that you think about how much money people might want to take out of the =
bank at once, and you try to make sure the bank has enough money to give th=
em. Modern banking regulation has rules like the liquidity coverage ratio (=
LCR) and net stable funding ratio (NSFR) to try to measure and regulate tha=
t risk, but =E2=80=94=C2=A0as Dan Davies  wrote in the Financial Times this=
 weekend =E2=80=94=C2=A0the US decided not to apply those rules to even ver=
y large regional banks like SVB. I am not sure how much that mattered =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0most banks don=E2=80=99t have enough liquidity to cover all of =
their deposits leaving at once, and SVB   might have met=C2=A0the requireme=
nts=C2=A0=E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s something regulators will consider. (Ra=
ising=C2=A0the liquidity requirements, to account for the speed of modern b=
ank runs, could also be on the table.)=09More generally, US financial regul=
ation tends to draw a sharp distinction between =E2=80=9Csystemically impor=
tant=E2=80=9D banks (like JPMorgan Chase & Co.) and just regular banks like=
 SVB. The systemically important banks are regulated and supervised much mo=
re strictly than the regular banks, and in recent years the difference has =
increased as   some rules were rolled back for regular banks.=C2=A0This dis=
tinction has always struck me as sort of incoherent, because =E2=80=9Csyste=
mic risk=E2=80=9D is not really a property of=C2=A0one bank=C2=A0but of=C2=
=A0the system. When SVB collapsed, its venture capitalist depositors clamor=
ed for a rescue by threatening systemic risk, by arguing that allowing them=
 to lose money would lead to broader panic across lots of banks: SVB wasn=
=E2=80=99t that big, but an uncontrolled failure at SVB would lead to many =
other failures at similar banks. They might well have been right! But  the =
obvious conclusion to draw from this=C2=A0is that biggish regional banks li=
ke SVB, at least, need to be subject to stricter regulations =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the sorts of rules that apply=C2=A0to the big banks =E2=80=94 because th=
ey are in fact systemically important. Not due to their individual size, bu=
t due to the (well known!) fact that a run on one bank can easily lead to r=
uns on other banks.=09Existing regulations do not seem to be particularly a=
ttuned to the risk of=C2=A0bad depositors. Bank regulators have historicall=
y given some thought to the question =E2=80=9Cwhat sorts of deposits are mo=
re likely to put a bank at risk by running all at once,=E2=80=9D and they t=
hink about  the risks of categories like brokered deposits, insured retail =
deposits, uninsured retail deposits, operational business deposits, etc. Bu=
t last month US banking regulators put out a =E2=80=9CJoint Statement on Li=
quidity Risks to Banking Organizations Resulting from Crypto-Asset=09Market=
 Vulnerabilities=E2=80=9D saying, in essence, that crypto companies are a p=
articularly risky class of depositors and banks should watch out for them. =
I   have argued that venture-backed tech firms are a similarly risky class =
of depositors, or at least they were for SVB. =E2=80=9CBanking organization=
s are neither prohibited nor discouraged from providing banking services to=
