=E2=80=99d be down=C2=A0more=C2=A0without these measures.) The rescue of Si=
licon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s depositors comes too late for Silicon Valley Ba=
nk=E2=80=99s shareholders, but it=E2=80=99s good for every similar bank=E2=
=80=99s shareholders.
As a matter of rough justice you could imagine the Fed looking at the=C2=A0=
most=C2=A0similar bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguably Signature, with its huge pro=
portion of uninsured deposits and its exposure to fast-money crypto/tech cu=
stomers =E2=80=94=C2=A0and saying =E2=80=9Cno, not you,=C2=A0your=C2=A0shar=
eholders are getting toasted.=E2=80=9D

The way for bank regulators to reduce the moral-hazard impact of the SVB re=
scue is to take some other banks=E2=80=99 shareholders out and shoot them.
Is that what happened?=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know! It=E2=80=99s possible tha=
t Signature was shut due to a traditional bank run. Reyes reports that =E2=
=80=9CSignature lost 20% of its deposits on Friday=E2=80=9D; Signature (and=
