I   wrote yesterday about the Fed=E2=80=99s Bank Term Funding Program. Bank=
s buy long-term bonds, mark them =E2=80=9Cheld to maturity,=E2=80=9D and th=
en when those bonds lose value the banks ignore it for accounting purposes.=
 But that only goes so far: The banks disclose the losses in footnotes to t=
heir financial statements, people sometimes notice, and when the losses get=
 too big there are runs. The BTFP is a way for the=C2=A0Fed=C2=A0to take ov=
er the job of ignoring those losses instead: The Fed promised to lend again=
st those bonds at 100 cents on the dollar, as though they hadn=E2=80=99t lo=
st value. The Fed is not subject to bank runs. The Fed can=C2=A0credibly=C2=
=A0ignore those losses; banks can only=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0ignore them.
I also wrote about Tether:
