y point, in the first section of this column, was that too much transparenc=
y can=C2=A0add=C2=A0to the fragility of a bank, that the Fed is providing a=
 valuable service by ignoring banks=E2=80=99 mark-to-market losses.
Byrne Hobart, whose Diff newsletter may or may not=C2=A0have played a role =
in bringing=C2=A0down Silicon Valley Bank,=C2=A0wrote today that =E2=80=9Ct=
he frequency of=C2=A0Diff/Money Stuff=C2=A0cross-linking is a good ad hoc m=
easure of financial conditions.=E2=80=9D He quotes my point about Tether an=
d goes on:
This post by Interfluidity=C2=A0is a wonderful exposition on the theme, arg=
uing that financial systems overcome the collective action problem that the=
re just aren't that many projects with an attractive level of risk and rewa=
rd to the person doing them, and that by disguising some of the risk, we ca=
n increase the positive externalities. This is an extreme view.
Yes! I=C2=A0think that post (=E2=80=9CWhy is finance so complex?=E2=80=9D) =
from Steve Randy Waldman at Interfluidity is a classic, I cite it often, an=
d it was what I had in mind as I was writing yesterday. Waldman describes b=
anking as, broadly speaking, an opacity mechanism for credit, a way for soc=
iety to take a lot of credit risk without the people taking that risk quite=
