ors, but that was good, and doesn=E2=80=99t really have much or any economi=
c cost to taxpayers given the likely selling price of the assets.=E2=80=9D


  [2] Isn=E2=80=99t it? You might disagree. But SVB was sort of embedded in=
 the culture of Silicon Valley, which meant things like (1) its executives =
probably thought of its startup customers as world-changing businesses rath=
er than creatures of interest rates and (2) they probably believed Silicon =
Valley=E2=80=99s hype that the tech ecosystem was cooperative and supportiv=
e and not just everyone looking out for themselves, so they didn=E2=80=99t =
expect their loyal venture capitalist depositors to turn on them so quickly=
. I highly recommend Ben Thompson=E2=80=99s Stratechery post from yesterday=
, =E2=80=9CThe End of Silicon Valley (Bank)," for his view on the demise of=
 Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s cooperative, repeat-player, infinite-game ethos. =
If you were an SVB executive a week ago, you might have still believed in t=
hat ethos. But if your response to all this is =E2=80=9Cthis was stupid and=
 they were taking stupid risks by being the bank of startups and betting bi=
g on duration,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s fine too.


  [3] Ooh I don=E2=80=99t know man, rates have rallied hard since SVB was r=
escued, and it was insolvent-ish because of a bad bet on rates. If you sell=
 the portfolio *today* maybe it is solvent enough to pay the equity somethi=
ng? I would not bet on the stock or anything but that would be a funny outc=
ome.


  [4] Asness was replying to this tweet from Jason Furman, which I agree wi=
th: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not particularly worried about moral hazard. The C=
EO, management & Board all losing their jobs. Equity going to zero. Bondhol=
ders won't be paid in full. These are all the entities that can effectively=
 monitor, is unrealistic to expect depositors to do much monitoring.=E2=80=
=9D


  [5] One way you know this is that lots of SVB depositors were earning zer=
o interest on their deposits. If they were knowingly or unknowingly taking =
risk in the hope of making a big return, or even a little return, it might =
be bad to bail them out. But they were not getting paid at all for taking r=
isk! It was just a bank account.


  [6] There is a  contrary view floating  around that in fact if you are a =
business with more than a few hundred thousand dollars in cash, you should =
develop expertise in cash management and bank risk, and use third-party pro=
ducts to spread that risk around to maximize FDIC coverage. Look: sure? Wha=
tever? I suppose that=E2=80=99s a useful business skill, but it feels like =
a skill that is useful in a second-best world. Better to make all the banks=
 safe so no one has to have this expertise.


  [7] No time to explain! Covered in   yesterday=E2=80=99s column!


